🧠 Introduction

List comprehensions provide a short and powerful way to create lists in Python.

They make code:

✔ Cleaner  
✔ Faster  
✔ More readable  

---

🔹 What is List Comprehension?

```text id="list_comp_def"
List comprehension is a concise way to create lists using a single line of code.
````

---

🎯 Why Use List Comprehensions?

✔ Reduce code length
✔ Improve readability
✔ Faster execution
✔ Easy filtering and transformations

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 Traditional Way vs List Comprehension

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

💻 Traditional Method

```python id="traditional_list"
numbers = []

for i in range(5):
    numbers.append(i)

print(numbers)
```

---

💻 Using List Comprehension

```python id="list_comp_basic"
numbers = [i for i in range(5)]

print(numbers)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="list_comp_output"
[0, 1, 2, 3, 4]
```

---

🔹 Syntax of List Comprehension

```python id="list_comp_syntax"
[expression for item in iterable]
```

---

📌 Components

| Component    | Meaning                |
| ------------ | ---------------------- |
| `expression` | Output value           |
| `item`       | Variable               |
| `iterable`   | Sequence or collection |

---

💻 Example: Square Numbers

```python id="square_example"
squares = [x * x for x in range(1, 6)]

print(squares)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="square_output"
[1, 4, 9, 16, 25]
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔍 Conditional List Comprehension

You can add conditions inside comprehensions.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

💻 Example: Even Numbers

```python id="even_example"
even_numbers = [x for x in range(10) if x % 2 == 0]

print(even_numbers)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="even_output"
[0, 2, 4, 6, 8]
```

---

💻 Example: Odd Numbers

```python id="odd_example"
odd_numbers = [x for x in range(10) if x % 2 != 0]

print(odd_numbers)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="odd_output"
[1, 3, 5, 7, 9]
```

---

🔄 if-else in List Comprehension

---

💻 Example

```python id="if_else_comp"
result = ["Even" if x % 2 == 0 else "Odd" for x in range(5)]

print(result)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="if_else_output2"
['Even', 'Odd', 'Even', 'Odd', 'Even']
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔤 List Comprehension with Strings

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

💻 Example

```python id="string_comp"
letters = [char.upper() for char in "python"]

print(letters)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="string_comp_output"
['P', 'Y', 'T', 'H', 'O', 'N']
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

📋 Nested List Comprehension

A list comprehension inside another comprehension.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

💻 Example

```python id="nested_comp"
matrix = [[j for j in range(3)] for i in range(3)]

print(matrix)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="nested_output2"
[[0, 1, 2], [0, 1, 2], [0, 1, 2]]
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔄 Flatten Nested Lists

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

💻 Example

```python id="flatten_example"
matrix = [[1, 2], [3, 4], [5, 6]]

flat = [num for row in matrix for num in row]

print(flat)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="flatten_output"
[1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
```

---

🧠 Dictionary Comprehension

Python also supports dictionary comprehensions.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

💻 Example

```python id="dict_comp"
squares = {x: x * x for x in range(5)}

print(squares)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="dict_output2"
{0: 0, 1: 1, 2: 4, 3: 9, 4: 16}
```

---

🔄 Set Comprehension

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

💻 Example

```python id="set_comp"
numbers = {x for x in range(5)}

print(numbers)
```

---

⚡ Generator Expression

Uses parentheses instead of square brackets.

---

💻 Example

```python id="generator_example"
nums = (x * x for x in range(5))

print(nums)
```

---

📌 Difference Between List & Generator

| List Comprehension | Generator               |
| ------------------ | ----------------------- |
| Uses `[]`          | Uses `()`               |
| Stores all values  | Generates values lazily |
| More memory        | Memory efficient        |

